# Engineering & Execution Rules

## Global Engineering and Execution Rules (Authoritative)

**Applies to:** `python`, `typescript`, `go`, `markdown`

---

## NON-NEGOTIABLE DIRECTIVE

**YOU MUST FOLLOW THESE RULES EXACTLY. THESE ARE NON-NEGOTIABLE.**

---

## WORK ORDER AUTHORITY

- When an **8090 Work Order** exists, all work **MUST** strictly follow it
- **DO NOT** add features, refactors, helpers, or improvements not explicitly specified
- If requirements are ambiguous, **STOP** and ask for clarification
- Each Work Order maps to **EXACTLY ONE** logical commit unless the user explicitly requests otherwise
- **Never** batch multiple Work Orders
- For repo bootstrap, documentation, investigation, or user-directed tasks without a Work Order, follow the user's explicit request and keep changes narrowly scoped

---

## EXECUTION & COMPLETION RULES

A Work Order is **NOT complete** until **ALL** of the following are true:

- All relevant tests pass locally
- Pre-commit hooks pass when configured
- CI passes when configured
- CD passes (if applicable)

Additional constraints:

- If CI or CD fails, diagnose and fix **immediately** before continuing
- **DO NOT** proceed to another Work Order while the pipeline is red
- If required tooling is not configured yet, state that clearly and do not invent substitute gates
- Assume your output will be executed **exactly as written**

---

## TEST STRATEGY (SIGNAL OVER NOISE)

- Target **>=50% coverage** with **HIGH-SIGNAL tests only**
- Every test must answer:
  **"Would this catch a real production bug?"**

### HIGH-SIGNAL TESTS (ALWAYS INCLUDE)

- API workflows & integration paths
- Business logic and validation
- Error handling & failure modes
- Security & auth flows
- Cross-component behavior

### LOW-SIGNAL TESTS (PROHIBITED)

- Field existence tests
- Getters / setters / constructors
- Framework behavior tests
- Configuration loading tests
- Coverage padding

---

## BUILD & CORRECTNESS

- Code **MUST** compile and type-check cleanly
- Python: `mypy` / `pyright` clean when configured
- TypeScript: strict `tsc` clean when configured
- **NEVER** emit code that cannot run
- **NEVER** access private/protected members outside their owning class/module
- **NEVER** bypass encapsulation "because it works"

---

## SECURITY & DEPENDENCIES

- **NEVER** commit secrets, credentials, tokens, keys, or real customer data
- Use environment variables or secret managers for sensitive configuration
- Add dependencies only when necessary and prefer established, maintained packages
- Do not introduce new infrastructure, services, or runtime requirements without explicit scope
- For database or schema changes, include migration, rollback, and compatibility considerations

---

## AGENTIC CODE GENERATION GUARDRAILS

- Treat generated code as untrusted until reviewed against the Work Order, tests, and project patterns
- Prefer existing architecture and local conventions over new abstractions
- Keep generated changes small, reviewable, and tied to a single intent
- Remove dead code, scaffolding, debug prints, and placeholder logic before completion
- Document non-obvious decisions in code comments or the final response

---

## GIT & PRE-COMMIT (ENFORCED)

- Pre-commit hooks are **REQUIRED** once configured
- Always run before completion when configured:

```bash
pre-commit run --all-files
```

---

## COMMIT MESSAGE CONVENTIONS

- Work Order commit subjects **MUST** start with `WO-X:` where `X` is the Work Order number
- Ad-hoc commit subjects **MUST** start with `ad-hoc:` when no Work Order applies
- Use exactly one logical commit per Work Order unless the user explicitly requests otherwise
- Do not mix Work Order implementation changes with unrelated ad-hoc setup changes
- Commit bodies must be written for agent and human PR reviewers and include:
  - `Intent`: why the change exists
  - `Scope`: what changed
  - `Out of scope`: what was deliberately not changed
  - `Validation`: what checks were run, or why a check was not applicable
  - `Review`: concise synthesized code-review outcome when an `agents-wip/<task>/synthesis.md` exists; include blocker status and fixes, not the full scratchpad
- Reference the Work Order number and title in the body when a Work Order exists
- Do **NOT** paste the entire Work Order into the commit body unless the user explicitly asks or the Work Order system is unavailable

---

## REVIEW & COMMIT GATE (HUMAN-IN-THE-LOOP)

- **DO NOT commit or push without explicit user approval.** A previous one-time "commit and push" instruction is **NOT** standing authorization for future Work Orders
- After implementing and validating a Work Order, **STOP** and present a concise summary plus the diff. Do not commit yet
- Offer (and, when requested, perform) a code review before committing — e.g., a dual-model review written to `agents-wip/`. Verify any blocking finding against ground truth before acting on it
- When creating a PR or commit after a review, include a short synthesized review note if available: mention that review ran, whether High/Medium blockers remain, and which blocking findings were fixed or accepted
- Only commit after the user explicitly approves; keep one logical commit per Work Order
- During long-running work, **checkpoint** with the user with brief progress updates rather than going silent

---

## AGENT SCRATCHPAD (agents-wip/)

- `agents-wip/` is an **EPHEMERAL, gitignored** agent working area. It is **NEVER** the source of truth
- The 8090 Work Orders/blueprints and committed code + commit messages remain authoritative
- Structure:
  - `agents-wip/WO-<n>/` for work-order tasks; `agents-wip/adhoc-<slug>/` for non-WO tasks
  - Within a task dir: `review-<model>-<UTC>.md`, `synthesis.md`, `notes.md`
  - `agents-wip/INDEX.md` is a manifest agents read first to orient
- Naming includes the agent/model and a UTC timestamp, e.g. `review-opus-20260608T0040Z.md`
- Findings are grouped **High / Medium / Low**; each item: `[file:line] issue — impact — suggested fix`
- Subagents performing analysis/review **MUST** write only within `agents-wip/` and **MUST NOT** modify repository source as part of analysis tasks
- Promote durable conclusions (decisions, fixes) into commits and, where applicable, Work Order comments; the scratchpad entry may then be deleted
